# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: servo-motors-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] A **closed-loop controller** or **feedback controller** is a control loop which incorporates feedback, in contrast to an *open-loop controller* or *non-feedback controller*.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] A closed-loop controller uses feedback to control states or outputs of a dynamical system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] In the case of linear feedback systems, a control loop including sensors, control algorithms, and actuators is arranged in an attempt to regulate a variable at a setpoint (SP).
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] An everyday example is the cruise control on a road vehicle; where external influences such as hills would cause speed changes, and the driver has the ability to alter the desired set speed.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The PID algorithm in the controller restores the actual speed to the desired speed in an optimum way, with minimal delay or overshoot, by controlling the power output of the vehicle's engine.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] Control systems that include some sensing of the results they are trying to achieve are making use of feedback and can adapt to varying circumstances to some extent.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] Open-loop control systems do not make use of feedback, and run only in pre-arranged ways.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] In some systems, closed-loop and open-loop control are used simultaneously.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] In such systems, the open-loop control is termed *feedforward* and serves to further improve reference tracking performance.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] A common closed-loop controller architecture is the PID controller.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The output of the system *y*(*t*) is fed back through a sensor measurement *F* to a comparison with the reference value *r*(*t*).
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The controller *C* then takes the error *e* (difference) between the reference and the output to change the inputs *u* to the system under control *P*.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] This kind of controller is a closed-loop controller or feedback controller.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] This is called a single-input-single-output (*SISO*) control system; *MIMO* (i.e., Multi-Input-Multi-Output) systems, with more than one input/output, are common.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] In such cases variables are represented through vectors instead of simple scalar values.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] For some distributed parameter systems the vectors may be infinite-dimensional (typically functions).
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] If we assume the controller *C*, the plant *P*, and the sensor *F* are linear and time-invariant (i.e., elements of their transfer function *C*(*s*), *P*(*s*), and *F*(*s*) do not depend on time), the systems above can be analysed using the Laplace transform on the variables.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The expression $H(s)={\frac {P(s)C(s)}{1+F(s)P(s)C(s)}}$ is referred to as the *closed-loop transfer function* of the system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The numerator is the forward (open-loop) gain from *r* to *y*, and the denominator is one plus the gain in going around the feedback loop, the so-called loop gain.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] If $|P(s)C(s)|\gg 1$ , i.e., it has a large norm with each value of *s*, and if $|F(s)|\approx 1$ , then *Y*(*s*) is approximately equal to *R*(*s*) and the output closely tracks the reference input.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism control technique widely used in control systems.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] A PID controller continuously calculates an *error value* *e*(*t*) as the difference between a desired setpoint and a measured process variable and applies a correction based on proportional, integral, and derivative terms.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] *PID* is an initialism for *Proportional-Integral-Derivative*, referring to the three terms operating on the error signal to produce a control signal.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The theoretical understanding and application dates from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analogue control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and later in industrial process computers.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The PID controller is probably the most-used feedback control design.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The desired closed loop dynamics is obtained by adjusting the three parameters *KP*, *KI* and *KD*, often iteratively by "tuning" and without specific knowledge of a plant model.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] Stability can often be ensured using only the proportional term.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The integral term permits the rejection of a step disturbance (often a striking specification in process control).
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] The derivative term is used to provide damping or shaping of the response.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] PID controllers are the most well-established class of control systems: however, they cannot be used in several more complicated cases, especially if MIMO systems are considered.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] However, in practice, a pure differentiator is neither physically realizable nor desirable due to amplification of noise and resonant modes in the system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/closed-loop-controller] Therefore, a phase-lead compensator type approach or a differentiator with low-pass roll-off are used instead.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Most servos are rotary actuators although other types are available.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Linear actuators are sometimes used, although it is more common to use a rotary actuator with a bellcrank and pushrod.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Some types, originally used as sail winches for model yachting, can rotate continuously.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A typical servo consists of a small electric motor driving a train of reduction gears.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A potentiometer is connected to the output shaft.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Some simple electronics provide a closed-loop servomechanism.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The position of the output, measured by the potentiometer, is continually compared to the commanded position from the control (i.e., the radio control).
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Any difference gives rise to an 'error signal' in the appropriate direction, which drives the electric motor either forwards or backwards, and moving the output shaft to the commanded position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] When the servo reaches this position, the error signal reduces and then becomes zero, at which point the servo stops moving.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] If the servo position changes from that commanded, whether this is because the command changes, *or* because the servo is mechanically pushed from its set position, the error signal will re-appear and cause the motor to restore the servo output shaft to the position needed.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Almost all modern servos are *proportional servos*, where this commanded position can be anywhere within the range of movement.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Early servos, and a precursor device called an *escapement*, could only move to a limited number of set positions.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Radio control servos are connected through a standard three-wire connection: two wires for a DC power supply and one for control, carrying a pulse-width modulation (PWM) signal.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Each servo has a separate connection and PWM signal from the radio control receiver.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] This signal is easily generated by simple electronics, or by microcontrollers such as the Arduino.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] This, together with their low cost, has led to their wide adoption for robotics and physical computing.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] RC servos use a three-pin 0.1"-spacing jack (female) which mates to standard 0.025" square pins.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The most common order is signal, +voltage, ground.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The standard voltage is 4.8 V DC, however 6 V and 12 V is also used on a few servos.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The control signal is a digital PWM signal with a 50 Hz frame rate.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Within each 20 ms timeframe, an active-high digital pulse controls the position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The pulse nominally ranges from 1.0 ms to 2.0 ms with 1.5 ms always being center of range.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Pulse widths outside this range can be used for "overtravel" - moving the servo beyond its normal range.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Each PWM defines a value that is used by the servo to determine its expected position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The first type is "absolute" and defines the value by the width of the active-high time pulse with an arbitrarily long period of low time.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The second type is "relative" and defines the value by the percentage of time the control is active-high versus low-time.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The "absolute" type allows up to eight servos to share one communication channel by multiplexing control signals using relatively simple electronics and is the basis of modern RC servos.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The "relative" type is the more traditional usage of PWM whereby a simple low-pass filter converts a "relative" PWM signal into an analog voltage.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The two types are both PWM because the servo responds to the width of the pulse.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] However, in the first case a servo may also be sensitive to pulse order.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The servo is controlled by three wires: ground, power, and control.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The servo will move based on the pulses sent over the control wire, which set the angle of the actuator arm.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The servo expects a pulse every 20 ms to gain correct information about the angle.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The width of the servo pulse dictates the range of the servo's angular motion.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A servo pulse of 1.5 ms width will typically set the servo to its "neutral" position (typically half of the specified full range), a pulse of 1.0 ms will set it to 0°, and a pulse of 2.0 ms to 90° (for a 90° servo).
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The physical limits and timings of the servo hardware varies between brands and models, but a general servo's full angular motion will travel somewhere in the range of 90° – 180° and the neutral position (45° or 90°) is almost always at 1.5 ms.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] This is the "standard pulse servo mode" used by all hobby analog servos.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A hobby digital servo is controlled by the same "standard pulse servo mode" pulses as an analog servo.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Some hobby digital servos can be set to another mode that allows a robot controller to read back the actual position of the servo shaft.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Some hobby digital servos can optionally be set to another mode and "programmed", so it has the desired PID controller characteristics when it is later driven by a standard RC receiver.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] RC servos are usually powered by the receiver, which in turn is powered by battery packs or an electronic speed controller (ESC) with an integrated or a separate battery eliminator circuit (BEC).
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Common battery packs are either NiCd, NiMH or lithium-ion polymer battery (LiPo) type.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Voltage ratings vary, but most receivers are operated at 5 V or 6 V.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Manufacturers and distributors of hobby RC servos often use a specific shorthand notation of mechanical properties of the servos.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Two figures are typically stated: angular speed of servo shaft rotation and mechanical torque produced on the shaft.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Speed is expressed as a time interval that a servo requires in order to rotate the shaft through a 60° angle.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Torque is expressed as weight that can be pulled up by the servo if it hangs from a pulley with a certain radius mounted on the shaft.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] For example, if a servo model is described as "0.2 s / 2 kg", that should be interpreted as "This servo rotates the shaft for 60° in 0.2 seconds, and it is able to pull up a 2 kg weight using a 1 cm radius pulley".
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] That is, that particular servo model rotates the shaft with the angular speed of (2π / 6) / 0.2 s = 5.2 rad/s while producing 2 kg × 9.81 m/s2 = 19.6 N force at 1 cm distance, i.e., it produces 19.6 N × 0.01 m = 0.196 Nm torque.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Although not in accordance with either the SI or Imperial unit system, the shorthand notation is in fact quite useful, as 60° shaft rotation commands, 1 cm long shaft cranks, as well as control rod "forces" in kilogram-force range are typical in hobby RC world.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Continuous-rotation servos are servos that do not have a limited travel angle, instead they can rotate continuously.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] They can be thought of as a motor and gearbox with servo input controls.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] In such servos the input pulse results in a rotational speed, and the typical 1.5 ms center value is the stop position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A smaller value should turn the servo clockwise and a higher one counterclockwise.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The earliest form of sequential (although not proportional) actuator for radio control was the *escapement*.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Like the device used in clocks, this escapement controls the release of stored energy from a spring or rubber band.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Each signal from the transmitter operates a small solenoid that then allows a two- or four-lobed pawl to rotate.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The pawl, like a clock, has two pallets so that the pawl can only rotate by one lobe's position, per signal pulse.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] This mechanism allows a simple keyed transmitter to give sequential control, i.e. selection between a number of defined positions at the model.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A typical four-lobe escapement used for rudder control is arranged so that the first and third positions are "straight ahead", with positions two and four as "left" and "right" rudder.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A single pulse from the first straight-ahead position allows it to move to left, or three pulses would select right.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A further single pulse returns to straight-ahead.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Such a system is difficult to use, as it requires the operator to remember which position the escapement is in, and so whether the next turn requires one or three pulses from the current position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] A development of this was the two-lobe pawl, where keying the transmitter continuously (and thus holding the solenoid pallet in place) could be used to select the turn positions with the same keying sequence, no matter what the previous position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Escapements were low-powered, but light-weight.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] They were thus more popular for model aircraft than model boats.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Where a transmitter and receiver had multiple control channels (e.g., a frequency-keyed reed receiver), then multiple escapements could be used together, one for each channel.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Even with single channel radios, a sequence of escapements could sometimes be cascaded.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Moving one escapement gave pulses that in turn drove a second, slower speed, escapement.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Escapements were disappearing from radio control, in favour of servos, by the early 1970s.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The Graupner Kinematic escapement could be used for rudder and electric motor control with one channel.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Short pulses for the motor; forward - stop - reverse - stop etc. and long pulses for the rudder; straight ahead - turn left - straight ahead - turn right - straight ahead etc.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The fly-ball actuator was introduced to R/C modelling in 1951 by Brayton Paul, and consisted of an electric motor and a centrifugal governor connected to a free-running axis that could, with the motor running, pull a rudder control rod by varying degrees.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] Used with a keyed radio system, this allowed some control over the rudder position by varying the key push timing.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servo-radio-control] The rudder would be pulled back by a spring when the motor speed decreased.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] In mechanical and control engineering, a **servomechanism** (also called **servo system**, or simply **servo**) is a control system for the position and its time derivatives, such as velocity, of a mechanical system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] It often includes a servomotor, and uses closed-loop control to reduce steady-state error and improve dynamic response.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] In closed-loop control, error-sensing negative feedback is used to correct the action of the mechanism.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] In displacement-controlled applications, it usually includes a built-in encoder or other position feedback mechanism to ensure the output is achieving the desired effect.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Following a specified motion trajectory is called **servoing**, where "servo" is used as a verb.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The *servo* prefix originates from the Latin word *servus* meaning 'slave'.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The term correctly applies only to systems where the feedback or error-correction signals help control mechanical position, speed, attitude or any other measurable variables.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] For example, an automotive power window control is not a servomechanism, as there is no automatic feedback that controls position—the operator does this by observation.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] By contrast a car's cruise control uses closed-loop feedback, which classifies it as a servomechanism.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] A common type of servo provides *position control*.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Commonly, servos are electric, hydraulic, or pneumatic.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] They operate on the principle of negative feedback, where the control input is compared to the actual position of the mechanical system as measured by some type of transducer at the output.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Any positive or negative difference between the actual and wanted values (an "**error signal**") is amplified (and converted) and used to drive the system's motor in the direction necessary to reduce or eliminate the error, e.g. through an H-bridge controller.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] This procedure is one widely used application of control theory.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Typical servos can give a rotary (angular) or linear output.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Speed control via a governor is another type of servomechanism.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The steam engine uses mechanical governors; another early application was to govern the speed of water wheels.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Prior to World War II the constant speed propeller was developed to control engine speed for maneuvering aircraft.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Fuel controls for gas turbine engines employ either hydromechanical or electronic governing.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Positioning servomechanisms were first used in military fire-control and marine navigation equipment.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Today servomechanisms are used in automatic machine tools, satellite-tracking antennas, remote control airplanes, automatic navigation systems on boats and planes, and antiaircraft-gun control systems.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Other examples are fly-by-wire systems in aircraft which use servos to actuate the aircraft's control surfaces, and radio-controlled models which use RC servos for the same purpose.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Many autofocus cameras also use a servomechanism to accurately move the lens.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] A hard disk drive has a magnetic servo system with sub-micrometer positioning accuracy.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] In industrial machines, servos are used to perform complex motion, in many applications.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] A *servomotor* is a specific type of motor that is combined with a rotary encoder or a potentiometer to form a servomechanism.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] This assembly may in turn form part of another servomechanism.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] A potentiometer provides a simple analog signal to indicate position, while an encoder provides position and usually speed feedback, which by the use of a PID controller allow more precise control of position and thus faster achievement of a stable position (for a given motor power).
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Potentiometers are subject to drift when the temperature changes whereas encoders are more stable and accurate.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Servomotors are used for both high-end and low-end applications.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] On the high end are precision industrial components that use a rotary encoder.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] On the low end are inexpensive radio control servos (RC servos) used in radio-controlled models which use a free-running motor and a simple potentiometer position sensor with an embedded controller.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The term *servomotor* generally refers to a high-end industrial component while the term *servo* is most often used to describe the inexpensive devices that employ a potentiometer.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Stepper motors are not considered to be servomotors, although they too are used to construct larger servomechanisms.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Stepper motors have inherent angular positioning, owing to their construction, and this is generally used in an open-loop manner without feedback.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] They are generally used for medium-precision applications.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] RC servos are used to provide actuation for various mechanical systems such as the steering of a car, the control surfaces on a plane, or the rudder of a boat.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Due to their affordability, reliability, and simplicity of control by microprocessors, they are often used in small-scale robotics applications.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] A standard RC receiver (or a microcontroller) sends pulse-width modulation (PWM) signals to the servo.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The electronics inside the servo translate the width of the pulse into a position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] When the servo is commanded to rotate, the motor is powered until the potentiometer reaches the value corresponding to the commanded position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] James Watt's steam engine governor is generally considered the first powered feedback system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The windmill fantail is an earlier example of automatic control, but since it does not have an amplifier or gain, it is not usually considered a servomechanism.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The first feedback position control device was the ship steering engine, used to position the rudder of large ships based on the position of the ship's wheel.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] His patented design was used on the SS Great Eastern in 1866.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Joseph Farcot may deserve equal credit for the feedback concept, with several patents between 1862 and 1868.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The telemotor was invented around 1872 by Andrew Betts Brown, allowing elaborate mechanisms between the control room and the engine to be greatly simplified.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Steam steering engines had the characteristics of a modern servomechanism: an input, an output, an error signal, and a means for amplifying the error signal used for negative feedback to drive the error towards zero.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The Ragonnet power reverse mechanism was a general purpose air or steam-powered servo amplifier for linear motion patented in 1909.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Electrical servomechanisms were used as early as 1888 in Elisha Gray's Telautograph.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Electrical servomechanisms require a power amplifier.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] World War II saw the development of electrical fire-control servomechanisms, using an amplidyne as the power amplifier.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Vacuum tube amplifiers were used in the UNISERVO tape drive for the UNIVAC I computer.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The Royal Navy began experimenting with Remote Power Control (RPC) on HMS Champion in 1928 and began using RPC to control searchlights in the early 1930s.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] During WW2 RPC was used to control gun mounts and gun directors.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Modern servomechanisms use solid state power amplifiers, usually built from MOSFET or thyristor devices.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The origin of the word is believed to come from the French "*Le Servomoteur*" or the slavemotor, first used by J.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] Farcot in 1868 to describe hydraulic and steam engines for use in ship steering.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The simplest kind of servos use bang–bang control.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] More complex control systems use proportional control, PID control, and state space control, which are studied in modern control theory.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomechanism] The servo bandwidth indicates the capability of the servo to follow rapid changes in the commanded input.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] A **servomotor** (or **servo motor** or simply **servo**) is a rotary or linear actuator that allows precise control of angular or linear position, velocity, and acceleration in a mechanical system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] It constitutes part of a servomechanism, and consists of a motor coupled to a sensor (for position feedback) and a controller (often a dedicated module designed for servomotors).
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Servomotors are not a specific class of motor, although the term *servomotor* is often used to describe a motor suitable for use in a closed-loop control system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Servomotors are used in robotics, CNC machinery, and automated manufacturing.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] NEMA ICS 16 defines several flange mounting patterns and corresponding bolt circles that are defined in millimeters or inches.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] A servomotor is a closed-loop servomechanism that uses position feedback (either linear or angular position) to control its motion and final position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The input to its control is a signal (either analog or digital) representing the desired position of the output shaft.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The motor is paired with a position encoder to provide position feedback (and potentially also speed feedback).
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The controller compares the measured position with the desired position to generate an error signal, which when fed back causes the motor to rotate in the direction needed to bring the shaft to the desired position.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The error signal falls to zero as the desired position is approached, stopping the motor.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] A simple servomotor uses position-only sensing via a potentiometer and bang-bang control of the motor, which only rotates at full speed or is stopped.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] This type of servomotor is not widely used in industrial motion control, but it forms the basis of the cheap servos in radio-controlled models.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] More sophisticated servomotors make use of an absolute encoder (a type of rotary encoder) to calculate the shaft's position and infer the speed of the output shaft.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] A variable-speed drive is used to control the motor speed.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Both of these enhancements, usually in combination with a PID control algorithm, allow the servomotor to be brought to its commanded position more quickly and more precisely, with less overshooting.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Servomotors are generally used as a high-performance alternative to the stepper motor.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Stepper motors have some inherent ability to control position, as they have built-in output steps.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] This often allows them to be used as an open-loop position control, without any feedback encoder, as their drive signal specifies the number of steps of movement to rotate, but for this, the controller needs to 'know' the position of the stepper motor on power up.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Therefore, on the first power-up, the controller will have to activate the stepper motor and turn it to a known position, e.g. until it activates an end limit switch.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] This can be observed when switching on an inkjet printer; the controller will move the ink jet carrier to the extreme left and right to establish the end positions.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] A servomotor can immediately turn to whatever angle the controller instructs it to, regardless of the initial position at power up, if an absolute encoder is used.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The lack of feedback of a stepper motor limits its performance, as the stepper motor can only drive a load that is well within its capacity, otherwise missed steps under load may lead to positioning errors and the system may have to be restarted or recalibrated.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The encoder and controller of a servomotor are an additional cost, but they optimize the performance of the overall system (for all of speed, power, and accuracy) relative to the capacity of the basic motor.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] With larger systems, where a powerful motor represents an increasing proportion of the system cost, servomotors have the advantage.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] There has been increasing popularity in closed-loop stepper motors in recent years.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] They act like servomotors but have some differences in their software control to get smooth motion.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The main benefit of an open-loop stepper motor is its relatively low cost.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] There is also no need to tune the feedback controller on an open-loop stepper system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The first servomotors were developed with synchros as their encoders.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Much work was done with these systems in the development of radar and anti-aircraft artillery during World War II.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Simple servomotors may use resistive potentiometers as their position encoder.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] These are only used at the very simplest and cheapest level and are in close competition with stepper motors.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] They suffer from wear and electrical noise in the potentiometer track.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Although it would be possible to electrically differentiate their position signal to obtain a speed signal, PID controllers that can make use of such a speed signal generally warrant a more precise encoder.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Modern servomotors use rotary encoders, either absolute or incremental.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Absolute encoders can determine their position at power-on but are more complicated and expensive.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Incremental encoders are simpler, cheaper, and work at faster speeds.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Incremental systems, like stepper motors, often combine their inherent ability to measure intervals of rotation with a simple zero-position sensor to set their position at start-up.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Instead of servomotors, sometimes a motor with a separate, external linear encoder is used.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] These motor + linear encoder systems avoid inaccuracies in the drivetrain between the motor and linear carriage, but their design is made more complicated as they are no longer a pre-packaged factory-made system.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] The type of motor is not critical to a servomotor, and different types may be used.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] At the simplest, brushed permanent magnet DC motors are used, owing to their simplicity and low cost.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Small industrial servomotors are typically electronically commutated brushless motors.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] For large industrial servomotors, AC induction motors are typically used, often with variable frequency drives to allow control of their speed.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] For ultimate performance in a compact package, brushless AC motors with permanent magnet fields are used, effectively large versions of Brushless DC electric motors.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Drive modules for servomotors are a standard industrial component.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Their design is a branch of power electronics, usually based on a three-phase MOSFET or IGBT H bridge.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] These standard modules accept a single direction and pulse count (rotation distance) as input.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] They may also include over-temperature monitoring, over-torque, and stall detection features.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] As the encoder type, gearhead ratio, and overall system dynamics are application specific, it is more difficult to produce the overall controller as an off-the-shelf module, and so these are often implemented as part of the main controller.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Most modern servomotors are designed and supplied around a dedicated controller module from the same manufacturer.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Controllers may also be developed around microcontrollers in order to reduce cost for large-volume applications.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Modern industrial servomotor systems employ digital servo drives or amplifiers to regulate current, velocity, and position using feedback loops.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] These drives communicate over industrial fieldbuses such as EtherCAT, CANopen, and POWERLINK, allowing coordinated motion among multiple axes.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Manufacturers including ADVANCED Motion Controls, Bosch Rexroth, and Yaskawa have developed such servo-drive families used in robotics, CNC machinery, and automated production equipment.
[src:servo-motors-deep/servomotor] Integrated servomotors are designed to include the motor, driver, encoder, and associated electronics into a single package.
